RENEWAL VERSUS REVISION

 

A petition to open a new charter school can be approved by the district for up to a five-year term. Near the end of the term, a charter school applies for “renewal” of its charter to continue operating for another five-year term. Education Code section 47605 requires the review and approval process for new and renewing charter petitions to take place over two board meetings: (i) public hearing, and (ii) action to grant/deny.

 

Within a five-year term, a charter school may request the district’s approval to revise its existing charter pursuant to Education Code section 47607. Proposed revisions may include a change in the school’s location, reassignment of special education responsibilities, expansion of grade levels, or other significant change.

 

CONCLUSION

RECOMMENDATION: Conduct a public hearing regarding the renewal of the charter of Health Sciences Middle School. The school is seeking a renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

BACKGROUND: Health Sciences Middle School (Health Sciences Middle) is one of two charter schools operated by the nonprofit public benefit corporation, Health Sciences High and Middle College, Inc. The other charter school is Health Sciences High and Middle College (Health Sciences High), whose charter expires on June 30, 2022. The public hearing is to consider the level of support for Health Sciences Middle.

 

Health Sciences Middle is seeking a renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023. When Health Sciences High renewed its charter in 2016, it included an expansion of grade levels to serve Grades 6-12, and anticipated that the Health Sciences Middle charter would expire and not be renewed. These decisions were made when it was determined that Health Sciences High would receive Proposition Z funds in an amount sufficient to purchase a facility large enough to house all of Grades 6-12. More recently, a property was identified for purchase that was smaller than initially planned, and it does not have the capacity to hold Grades 6-12. Health Sciences Middle is requesting a renewal of its charter for a five-year term, as required by statute, but it plans to cease all middle school operations after the current sixth grade class completes middle school in June 2020. Although the Health Sciences High charter is approved for Grades 6-12, based on the updated facility projections, the school plans to only serve Grades 9-12 in the future, and does not want to have middle school test scores mixed in to the high school scores for only a two-year period.

 

Both Health Sciences High and Health Sciences Middle are located at 3910 University Avenue, which is within the attendance boundaries of Central Elementary, Wilson Middle, and Hoover High School. Currently, Health Sciences Middle serves Grades 6-8, and Health Sciences High serves Grades 9-12.

“Innovations Academy educational program is driven by three guiding principles: Purposeful Learning, Compassionate Connection and Self Expression.” The program components include field study experiences, participation in Project Based Service Learning, and a campus Explorations Program. The curriculum is grounded in a constructivist philosophy, and is supplemented with neurocognitive education (nutrition, movement, multi-sensory approach, learning styles and modalities, and brain based learning mindfulness), and a family support program that serves as a parent education tool.

 

In its charter petition, Innovations states that it offers an embedded social emotional program that infuses confidence and self-awareness in children. Following progressive education models, the school has created an academic program in the absence of all rewards and punishments, where students learn to do the right thing based on open communication with kind and firm boundaries. The Responsive Classroom approach to teaching emphasizes social, emotional, and academic growth.

 

Per the charter petition at page 8, at its current location, Innovations is the only classroom-based charter school within a 12 mile radius. Innovations also offers families a 2-day or 3-day independent study option. Over the past nine years, the participation in this program has grown from 10 to 53 students. The 2-day program will not exceed 20% of the school’s total population.

 

Since moving to the Scripps Ranch location, the school has seen an increase in the number of students with disabilities who are choosing the school. Approximately 20% of the total enrollment is made up of students with disabilities. The renewal petition indicates that, “[i]n some of our classes as many as 50% of the students have learning disabilities.”

 

**END SECTION**

 

Innovations is seeking renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023. Staff recommends that the board grant the charter renewal with the following clarifications:

 

Clarification 1: Approve Legal Status on page 107 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

Consistent with the statutory intent of Education Code section 47604 (c), the San Diego Unified School District shall not be liable for the debts or obligations of Innovations Academy. The School shall indemnify, defend, save, and hold the District, the Board, the Superintendent, employees, officers, directors, subcontractors, agents and authorized volunteers (collective "employees") harmless against any and all claims, demands, suits, costs, judgment or other forms of liability to third parties, actual or claimed, or whatsoever kind or character, including attorneys' fees, brought against the School or School employees for injury to property or persons, occurring or allegedly occurring in, on or about the school from conduct committed by the School or by its employees, officers, directors, subcontractors, agents. The District will not be liable for any actions taken by the School. Innovations Academy will purchase and maintain, as necessary, general liability, automotive liability, errors and omissions, sexual misconduct, property, workers compensation and unemployment insurance policies, in amounts that are compliant with district requirements as stated in the annual Operations Agreement.[1] either as part of the District's insurance programs or its own insurance program. If the charter school purchases its own insurance, it shall be equivalent to the District's program with respect to limits and coverage.

 

[1] This same clarification shall be included in the Legal Status and Civil Liability Effects section (beginning on page 147) of the renewal charter with regard to the insurance requirements.

 

 

Clarification 2: Approve TB Testing on page 116 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

Faculty, staff and volunteers will be tested for tuberculosis prior to commencing employment and working with students, and on an ongoing basis as required by Education Code Section 49406.

 

Clarification 2: Approve Annual Audit on page 124 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

An annual fiscal audit of Innovations Academy, required under the Charter Schools Act, will be conducted by an auditor with experience in education finance and will use Generally Accepted Accounting Principles ("GAAP"). The audit will be supervised by the Director. Innovations Academy will share the results with the District, the County Superintendent of Schools, the State Controller, and the California Department of Education by the 15th of December of each year. ’s Administrative Director of Business Services or designated staff and any other entities (such as the State Board of Education, the California Department of Education, the County Office of Education, or any other agency as the State Board of Education may direct) as required by law. All exceptions and deficiencies and their remedies will be resolved to the District’s standard. The Board of the School will resolve audit exceptions and deficiencies in a timely fashion and follow the dispute resolution process if exceptions and deficiencies cannot be resolved.

 

The District shall provide and/or perform the supervisory oversight tasks and duties specified and/or necessary for the implementation of this charter for a fee, as specified in California Education Code section 47613. not exceed one percent of the average daily attendance funds provided to Innovations Academy, or not to exceed three percent, if the School uses District facilities, pursuant to the terms of the Charter School Act.

 

Clarification 4: Approve Suspension and Expulsion Policy on page 132 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

Only the Director (Principal) or the Director’s designee may recommend expulsion of a student or refer a student for an expulsion hearing. Students recommended for expulsion are entitled to a hearing to determine whether the student should be expelled. Unless postponed for good cause, the hearing shall be held within thirty (30) school days after the Director or designee determines that the Pupil has committed an expellable offense, and shall be in compliance with the requirements of Education Code section 47605(b)(5)(J).

 

Clarification 5: Approve Dispute Resolution on page 140 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

In the event of a dispute between the Charter School and the District, Charter School staff, employees and Board members of the Charter School and District both parties agree to first frame the issue in written format (“dispute statement”) and refer the issue to the Superintendent’s Designee and Director or Designee of the Charter School. In the event that the District Board of Trustees believes that the dispute relates to an issue that could lead to issuance of a notice of violation supporting revocation of the charter in accordance with Education Code Section 47607, the Charter School requests that this shall be noted in the written dispute statement, although it recognizes is cannot legally bind the District to do so. However, participation in the dispute resolution procedures outlined in this section shall not be interpreted to impede or act as a pre-requisite to the District’s ability to proceed with revocation in accordance with Education Code Section 47607.

 

The Innovations Academy Director or Designee and Superintendent’s Designee shall informally meet and confer in a timely fashion to attempt to resolve the dispute, not later than 5 business days from receipt of the dispute statement at the earliest mutually convenient time. In the event that this informal meeting fails to resolve the dispute, both parties shall identify two Board members representatives from their respective boards organizations who shall jointly meet with the Superintendent or Designee and the Director or Designee of the Charter School and attempt to resolve the dispute within 15 business days from receipt of the dispute statement at the earliest mutually convenient time. If this joint meeting fails to resolve the dispute, the Superintendent or Designee and the Director or Designee shall meet to jointly identify a neutral third party mediator to engage the Parties in a mediation session designed to facilitate resolution of the dispute. The format of the mediation session shall be developed jointly by the Superintendent and the Director parties. Mediation shall be held within sixty (60) business days of receipt of the dispute statement at the earliest mutually convenient time. The costs of the mediator shall be split equally between the District and Innovations Academy. If mediation does not resolve the dispute either party may pursue any other remedy available under the law. All timelines in this section may be revised upon mutual written agreement of the District and Innovations Academy. The Charter School shall be solely responsible for its attorney’s fees and any other costs or expenses arising from a dispute.

 

The San Diego Unified School District may inspect or observe any part of the School at any time, but shall provide reasonable notice to the Director of Innovations Academy prior to any observation or inspection.

 

Clarification 6: Approve School Closure on page 142 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

Innovations Academy will designate a responsible entity to conduct closure-related activities. Notification of the closure will be made promptly to the parents or guardians of pupils, the authorizing entity, county office of education, special education local plan area (SELPA) in which the school participates, retirement systems in which school employees participate, and the California Department of Education. The notification will include the effective date of closure, names of and contact information for the person(s) to whom reasonable inquiries may be made regarding the closure, the pupils’ school districts of residence, and the manner in which students may obtain copies of pupil records, including specific information on completed courses and credits that meet graduation requirements.

 

As applicable, Innovations Academy will provide parents, students and the District with copies of all appropriate student records and will otherwise assist students in transferring to their next school. All transfers of student records will be made in compliance with the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (“FERPA”) 20 U.S.C. § 1232g. Innovations Academy will ask the District to store original records of Charter School students. All other records of the School shall be transferred and maintained to the District upon School closure in accordance with applicable law. District property that is transferred to Innovations Academy together with the facilities remains District property, is not an asset of Innovations Academy, and must be returned to the District when Innovations Academy closes (to comply with 47605(a)(1).

 

As soon as reasonably practical, Innovations Academy will prepare final financial records. The School will also have an independent audit completed as soon as reasonably practical, which period is generally no more than six months after closure. The School will pay for the final audit and all other closure-related activities. The audit will be prepared by a qualified Certified Public Accountant selected by the School and will be provided to the District promptly upon its completion. The school or its designated representative for closure-related activities will ensure the completion and filing of any annual reports required pursuant to Education Code section 47604.33.

 

Clarification 7: Approve Information Exchange on page 146 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

 

Innovations Academy agrees to promptly respond to all reasonable inquiries, including inquiries regarding its financial records. Innovations Academy records will be treated as public records under the California Public Records Act. The District may inspect or observe any part of Innovations Academy at any time. The District agrees it will not do so unreasonably, without notice or by causing a disruption of student instruction or Innovations Academy operations except in the case of an emergency.

 

Innovations Academy shall permit the District to inspect and receive copies of all records relating to its operation, including financial, personnel and pupil records, for articulated oversight purposes, provided that District maintains the confidentiality of such records to the extent required by law, and unless law prohibits disclosure to the District of any such records. The Academy shall promptly comply with all such reasonable written requests. Pursuant to Education Code 47607, the District shall have the right to inspect or observe any part of Innovations Academy at any time, upon reasonable notice.

 

RENEWAL ANALYSIS

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

Staff has visited Innovations annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board members, teachers, administrators, financial managers, parents, and/or students. During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.

  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.

  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(g).

     

    Assembly Bill (“AB”) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 through 2016-17 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;

  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or

  3. Alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

Teachers will use effective pedagogical strategies to engage students in high quality, vigorous inquiry based learning including the use of firm classroom management and behavioral interventions and supports
  • Students and parents receive clear feedback about their progress
  • Parents express satisfaction in communication from school
  • Student behavior is tracked and analyzed to inform decision making
  • 100% of teachers receive professional development on multiple academic and social emotional strategies
  • New teachers report feeling supported in an annual survey
  • Maintain low suspension rates
  • 100% of teachers will have access to instructional coaching
  • 100% of students will have access to a variety of arts instruction
  • Teachers are given support in the classroom

Provide high quality, standards aligned materials and resources to teachers and students within facilities maintained for optimal learning
  • 100% of students will have access to instruction in a variety of arts
  • 100% of students will have access to Common Core aligned instructional materials
  • 100% of students will have access to technology that enhances their learning
  • 100% of classroom teachers will be appropriately credentialed and assigned

Develop a structure for ongoing analysis and intervention of student absences and tardies
  • Set a baseline for absences over the past year and tardies
  • Decreased number of absences
  • Increased intervention throughout the year
  • Decreased number of tardies
  • Decreased number of students who are absent or tardy repeatedly
  • Increased work while home for absent students

Develop stronger parent partnerships through effective communication tools, increased means of input and parent education
  • 100% of parents will receive specific information pertaining to their child’s academic and social emotional learning
  • 100% of parents will be given parent education regarding ways to extend academic learning at home
  • 100% of parents will be provided multiple opportunities to participate in school based activities
  • 100% of parents will participate in at least one school event
  • Parents will respond to a parent survey
  • Parents will be provided parent educational opportunities and information about child developmental needs

FINANCES

 

District staff reviewed and analyzed the five-year budget and three-year cash flow submitted by Innovations, as well as previously submitted financial reports including, but not limited to, the 2016-17 audited Financial Report. Per the fiscal year 2016-17 audit report, Innovations’ net assets increased $103,805, with ending assets totaling $1,761,511, which met the District’s reserve requirement. As of June 30, 2017, available cash of $1,866,123 was sufficient to satisfy current liabilities of $104,612. The school is fiscally solvent at this time.

 

Annual revenues and expenditures are identified by source. Revenue assumptions relate to the applicable state and federal funding formulas. LCFF revenues presented are within range of district staff’s calculations. Innovations has projected operational surpluses of $7,197, $64,340, $210,424, $27,308, and $27,182 for fiscal years 2018-19 through 2022-23, respectively. The ending net position each year meets the district’s minimum reserve requirement with the greater of 3% of expenditures or $50,000.

e3 (engage, educate, empower) uses a multidisciplinary approach to learning that is central to the curriculum and instructional design. e3 offers a weeklong Summer Bridge program each August to support incoming ninth graders and any new students transferring to e3. e3 accepts students at all grade levels, year round, if space is available.

**END SECTION**

 

e3 is seeking renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023. Staff recommends that the board grant the charter renewal with the following concerns and clarifications as noted:

 

  1. The school failed to post its 2015-16 School Accountability Report Card (“SARC”) by the required date: In monitoring the annual operations of e3 charter school, it was determined that the school did not meet the statutorily required publishing date of February 1, 2017, for its 2015-16 SARC. California Education Code section 35256(c) requires the publishing of an annual SARC “on or before February 1 of each year.” On several dates before and after February 1, 2017, district staff checked the online SARC webpage. On June 27, 2017, staff noted that the SARC still had not been published for e3. Based on the “created” date in the SARC’s “document properties,” it appears that the document was created/published on August 7, 2017, six months past the required deadline.

     

  2. The school has not complied with the Political Reform Act, Government Code sections 87000 et seq. for purposes of Statement of Economic Interest (Form 700): In monitoring the annual operations of e3, it was determined that the school has not complied with the requirements of Government Code sections 87000 et seq., including the completion and filing of annual Statements of Economic Interest (Form 700s).

     

    In its original charter, and in the renewal documents, e3 indicated that it will comply with the Political Reform Act, Government Code sections 87000 et seq. Compliance with this requires that designated positions complete and submit an annual Form 700 to the San Diego County Board of Supervisors.

     

    As part of each annual site visit, district staff requests that all Form 700s from the prior year be produced for review. In every year, e3 has failed to provide the majority of the Forms, despite the fact that a written request for them to be produced for the site visit is sent well in advance of each visit. The annual site visit notes regarding the Form 700s indicate that, in 2014-15, no Forms were provided for review. At the 2015-16 site visit (May 25, 2016), no 2015 Forms were provided, but two 2014 Forms were provided for school leaders (Griffith and Xu). No Forms were provided for any of the eleven board members. At the 2016-17 site visit (January 10, 2017), three 2015 Forms were provided for school leaders (Griffith, Xu and Ward). Forms were provided for only two of the twelve board members (Katz and Ochoa). At the 2017-18 site visit (October 30, 2017), no 2016 Forms were provided. The few 2015 Forms provided at the prior year’s site visit were included.

     

  3. The charter and bylaws require “staggered” board member terms, which does not appear to be being implemented: Page 95 of the charter states that the “Board of Directors consists of three (3) to fifteen (15) members serving staggered three-year terms.” Based on the current board roster included in the renewal documents, eight of the nine current board members have the same term of “June 2016 – June 2019.” Only one board member has a different term (June 2015–June 2018).

     

    The bylaws state that members of the “initial board” shall stagger their terms by dividing members into three groups, with each group having a different term length (one year, two years, or three years). It is unclear if this is the “staggering” that e3 intends to carry on, as all board members, with the exception of one, now have the same term, and all board members serve a three-year term.

     

  4. Approve Instructional Calendar on page 60 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    The e3 Instructional Calendar offers a total of 177 days of instruction and exceeds the minimum number of minutes as set forth in Education Code section 47612.5, and the number of school days required by California Code of Regulations, title 5, section 11960.

     

      e3 offers a total of 178 177 days of instruction each year, and exceeds minimum instructional minutes requirements by 7,619.

     

  5. Approve Special Education on page 70 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    Pursuant to Education Code Section 47641(a), e3 Civic High participates as a Local Education Agency (LEA) in El Dorado County Charter SELPA for the purpose of compliance with federal and state law and for eligibility for federal and state special education funds. e3 Civic High has been a member in good standing of El Dorado County Charter SELPA since April 24, 2014. A change in LEA status or SELPA membership shall not require a material revision of this charter.

     

  6. Approve Educational Design as Guide on page 85 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    The educational design outlined in this petition represents a meaningful guide for developing specific educational programs, scholar outcomes, and methods of assessment at e3 Civic High. Some modifications to what is presented in the petition may occur at the discretion of the Board or the CEO/Executive Director to best meet the needs of the scholars enrolled at e3 Civic High and its staff, but would not constitute a materially significant change in the petition. The charter school authorizer would be informed of any materially significant change to the educational design outlined in the petition, prior to any changes being implemented at the school.

     

  7. Approve Employee Qualifications on page 103 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    By May 4, 2018, e3 will submit additional information regarding employee qualifications for the Chief of Academic Innovation position. The additional information is necessary as this position provides “coaching and mentoring for all faculty…,” as stated in the measurable pupil outcomes section of the charter.

     

  8. Approve Expulsion Procedures on page 120 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    A scholar may be expelled by the Board of Directors upon the recommendation of an Administrative Panel to be assigned by the CEO/Executive Director as needed. The Administrative Panel should consist of at least three members who are certificated and neither a teacher of the scholar or member of the Board of Directors, and who are compliant with the “neutral officer” requirements as stated in California Education Code section 47605(b)(5)(J). The Administrative Panel may recommend expulsion of any scholar found to have committed an expellable offense.

     

  9. Approve Medication in School on page 105 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    e3 Civic High adheres to Education Code Section 49423 regarding administration of medication in school, and Education Code Section 49414 for emergency epinephrine auto-injectors.

     

  10. Approve Dispute Resolution Process on pages 132 and 133 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    In the event of a dispute between e3 Civic High and the District regarding the terms of this charter or any other issue regarding the school and District relationship, both parties agree to apprise the other, in writing, of the specific disputed issue(s). In the event the initiating party District believes the dispute relates to an issue that could potentially lead to revocation of the charter, e3 requests that this shall be specifically noted in the written dispute statement, although it recognizes that it cannot legally bind the District to do so. At the earliest mutually convenient date, Not later than five (5) business days from receipt of the dispute statement, an e3 Civic High representative and a District representative shall informally meet and confer to attempt to resolve the dispute. If this joint meeting fails to resolve the dispute, two representatives from each organization the e3 Civic High representative and the District representative shall meet again within fifteen (15) business days at the earliest mutually convenient date to attempt to resolve the dispute. If this meeting fails to resolve the dispute, a District representative and an e3 representative shall meet to identify a neutral third-party mediator to assist in dispute resolution. The format of the third-party mediation process shall be developed jointly by the representatives. The mediation shall be held within thirty (30) business days of receipt of the dispute statement. All timelines in this section may be revised upon mutual written agreement at the earliest mutually convenient date.

     

  11. Approve Liability on page 136 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    The corporate bylaws shall provide for indemnification of the Board of Directors, officers, agents, and employees. e3 Civic High retains general liability insurance, auto liability, errors and omissions, sexual misconduct, worker’s compensation, Board Members and Officer’s insurance, and fidelity bonding to secure against financial risks. Insurance amounts will be in compliance with district requirements as stated in the annual Operations Agreement. determined by recommendation of the District and the school’s insurance company for schools of similar size, location, and scholar population. The District shall be named an additional insured on the general liability insurance.

     

  12. Approve Administrative Services on page 137 of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    The details of the relationship between the District and e3 Civic High are delineated in a Memorandum of Understanding (“MOU”). e3 Civic High shall retain the right to separately purchase administrative or other services from the District or any other agency. Such services may include personnel review for credential and criminal purposes, police services, or other services that shall be available to non-profit schools. The specific terms and costs for these services shall be the subject of a mutually agreed upon Memorandum of Understanding. e3 Civic High understands that current law mandates that the District provide oversight as required by California Education Code section 47604.32. and performance monitoring services, including monitoring school and scholar performance data, financial statements and audit reports, enrollment verification, performing annual site visits, engaging in the Dispute Resolution Process, and considering charter amendment and renewal requests.

     

  13. Approve Conflict of Interest Policy in Appendix C of the charter petition renewal document as clarified below:

     

    The Conflict of Interest Policy, included as Appendix C in e3’s charter renewal document, does not satisfy Government Code Sections 87000 et seq., as required by the charter. By May 4, 2018, e3 will provide a board-approved Conflict of Interest Policy that complies with all required provisions stated in Government Code Sections 87000 et seq..

     

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

Staff has visited e3 annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board members, teachers, administrators, financial managers, parents, and/or students. During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.

  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.

  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(g).

     

    Assembly Bill (“AB”) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 through 2016-17 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;

  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or

  3. Alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

     

    e3 began operating in 2013, the first year that the API testing was suspended, and therefore does not have any historical API or decile ranking data. The only applicable renewal criteria are those that consider comparison data and alternative measures. As a result, the academic analysis is limited to SBAC/CAASPP data, comparison school data[2], and alternative measures data.

FINANCES

 

District staff reviewed and analyzed the five-year budget (includes current FY 2017-18) and cash flow submitted by e3, as well as previously submitted financial reports including, but not limited to, the 2016-17 Audited Financial Report. Per the fiscal year 2016-17 audit report, e3’s net assets increased $336,769, with ending assets totaling $2,281,998, which met the District’s reserve requirement of the greater of 3% of expenditures or $50,000. As of June 30, 2017, available cash of $2,554,928 was sufficient to satisfy current liabilities of $297,098. The school is fiscally solvent at this time.

 

Annual revenues and expenditures are identified by source. LCFF revenues presented are within range of district staff’s calculations. E3 is projected to have operational surpluses of $197,248, $185,407, $147,691, $97,142, and $57,157 for fiscal years 2017-18 through 2021-22, respectively. The ending net position each year meets the district’s minimum reserve requirement with the greater of 3% of expenditures or $50,000.

 

Over the past four years, e3 has been compliant in addressing all financial reporting timeline requirements, and timely payments to the district.

 

District staff recommends that the board grant the renewal of the charter petition of e3 for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023.

E. OPERATIONAL MATTERS RESERVED FOR THE BOARD
Subject
5. National University Academy 1001 STEAM: Action on Charter Petition to Establish New Charter School
Meeting
Mar 6, 2018 - Regular Charter Meeting, 5:00 P.M.
Type
Action

RECOMMENDATION: Deny the charter petition to establish National University Academy 1001 STEAM (“NUA”) as a new charter school. Staff recommends the board adopt, in support of a denial, the following written factual findings.

 

FINDINGS:

  1. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on a budget that presents a financial plan that is not fiscally viable because it overstates revenues and understates expenses, resulting in negative ending fund balances.

  2. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because on November 14, 2017, the National University Academy governing board authorized a $253,125 transfer of funds to one of its charter schools near Sacramento.

  3. The NUA petition does not contain a reasonably comprehensive description of how the school will support Socioeconomically Disadvantaged Students.

  4. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on overly optimistic enrollment projections.

  5. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on unrealistic Attendance Rate increases.

  6. The petition does not contain a reasonably comprehensive description of the Governance structure of the school based on an inadequate Conflict of Interest Code.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The public hearing to consider the level of support for the petition to establish NUA was held on February 6, 2018. NUA previously submitted a charter petition to the district which was denied by the board on May 16, 2017. Kimberleigh Kopp is the Lead Petitioner.

 

National University Academy is currently authorized by Lakeside Union School District. The current charter petition was submitted to the district as part of a transition plan to make the one site within the district’s boundaries compliant with current geographic requirements. The petition is for one non-classroom based site that will serve Grades 6-12 at a non-district facility located at 3678 Aero Court, San Diego, 92123, which is located within the attendance boundaries of Angier Elementary, Taft Middle School, and Kearny High School. National University Academy also operates other sites outside of the district’s boundaries under the charter petition authorized by Lakeside.

 

NUA proposes to be authorized by San Diego Unified School District as of July 1, 2018, and is requesting a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023.

 

The charter petition for NUA describes a non-classroom-based educational program with a STEAM focus. Page 24 of the petition states that, “NUA 1001 STEAM offers a unique independent study program that provides students in grades 6-12 with both site-based and online support.” Students also participate in project-based learning activities, and are supported by professors from National University’s School of Engineering and Computing (page 21). The five core values of NUA are Innovation, Opportunity, Achievement, Collaboration and Flexibility (page 27).

 

On page 38 of the petition, the school has indicated that its students come from 22 zip codes within San Diego Unified School District’s boundaries. “The majority of the students come from the following areas: Oak Park (10.78%), Linda Vista (20.58%), Clairemont (7.84%), Kearny Mesa (14.70%) and Mira Mesa (15.68%).”

 

The National University Academy governing board is the decision-making body for the charter school. The school’s bylaws require a minimum of eight and maximum of fifteen governing board members. There are currently seven governing board members. NUA has indicated that it reserves a seat on the board for a representative that is appointed by the authorizing district. The current board is summarized in the following table.

The intent of the Legislature in enacting the Charter Schools Act of 1992, as stated in California Education Code Section 47601, included providing opportunities for the establishment of schools that operate independently from school districts, in order to expand pupil learning experiences, encourage the use of different and innovative teaching methods, and provide pupils with expanded choices in the types of educational opportunities available in public schools.

 

Education Code Section 47605(b) states that the governing board of a school district shall not deny a petition for the establishment of a charter school unless it makes written factual findings, specific to the particular petition, setting forth specific facts to support one or more of the following findings:

    1. The charter school presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school.

    2. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the petition.

    3. The petition does not contain the number of signatures required by subdivision (a).

    4. The petition does not contain an affirmation of each of the conditions described in subdivision (d).

    5. The petition does not contain reasonably comprehensive descriptions.

 

FINDINGS:

 

1. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on a budget that presents a financial plan that is not fiscally viable because it overstates revenues and understates expenses, resulting in negative ending fund balances. Staff analysis concludes that NUA will have projected negative ending fund balances of $263,425, $201,001, and $96,168, with zero percent reserve for fiscal years 2018-19 through 2020-21, respectively.

 

NUA submitted its petition to the District prior to the release of the 2018-19 Governor’s Proposed State Budget. Since the release of the budget, several planning factors and assumptions have changed, including the LCFF gap funding percentage, COLA, rates per ADA for categorical program funding, and employer contribution rates for pensions.
 

On page E-65 of the charter document, NUA has indicated that it expects National University Academy to distribute 12.9% of its ending net position to NUA, which represents the percentage of ADA attributable to the Aero Court site. 2017-18 LCFF revenues were incorrectly estimated by petitioners. They used the LCFF calculator, and estimated revenues as if NUA began in 2017-18. District staff estimated the organization’s 2017-18 LCFF revenues based on existing assumptions, and then applied a rate of 12.9% to the total to calculate NUA’s portion.
 

Overstated Revenues:
As an independent study (non-classroom based) program, NUA must apply for funding determinations from the State, which range from 70% to 100% funding. In July 2017, the State determined that National University Academy, based on its 2015-16 data, qualified to receive only 70% of its LCFF funding for fiscal years 2017-18 and 2018-19, due to it not meeting the spending requirements that would qualify for 100% funding. However, NUA submitted a budget in the petition using 100% funding. The table below reflects the current 70% State funding determination, which results in the current 2017-18 year having a negative ending fund balance of approximately $235,326 that is attributable to the Aero Court site.

NUA intends to be a school of the District for special education purposes in 2018-19, and will apply to be an LEA member with El Dorado County Charter SELPA beginning in 2019-20. In 2018-19, the district would receive State and Federal special education revenues while providing special education staff and services to the school. The budget for 2018-19 includes special education State revenue from El Dorado that NUA would not receive as a school of the district, resulting in overstated revenue of $65,637.00.

 

Understated Expenses

According to page 98 of the petition, and confirmed by the lead petitioner, NUA intends to be a school of the district for the purposes of special education in accordance with Education Code Section 47641(b). As a school of the district, the district would receive State and Federal special education revenues while providing special education staff and services to NUA. As a school of the district, NUA will be required to contribute to the unfunded costs of the district’s special education. The current contribution estimate is $2,005.59 per student enrolled. This contribution was not included in the budget, resulting in understated expenses of roughly $286,799 in the first year. It is noted that this was also a finding in the previous charter petition that was submitted.

2. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because on November 14, 2017, the National University Academy governing board authorized a $253,125 transfer of funds to one of its charter schools, NUA Robla, near Sacramento. This transfer resulted in local funds generated by and for students residing in San Diego, Riverside, and Orange Counties being used for a charter school located hundreds of miles away.

 

National University Academy currently operates ten school sites within Southern California. As summarized in the table below, National University Academy has a history of closing its own charter schools, including NUA Robla, due to financial difficulties arising from low enrollment.

On November 14, 2017, the National University Academy governing board, which oversees the organization’s ten charter schools, granted approval to use $253,125 in reserve funds to pay for NUA Robla. NUA Robla did not achieve ADA requirements as per the Charter School Start-Up Grant and owed these funds back to the California Department of Education (“CDE”). NUA Robla opened in August 2014, and closed in June 2016, due to low enrollment. Staff was unable to locate any enrollment for the school for the 2014-15 year. The 2015-16 P-2 certified data available on the CDE website indicates that NUA Robla had total funded ADA of 4.33. It is concerning that LCFF/ADA funds generated by students attending National University Academy sites in Southern California were used to pay for a school several hundred miles away in the Sacramento area.

 

3. The NUA petition does not contain a reasonably comprehensive description of how the school will support Socioeconomically Disadvantaged Students. On pages 90-98, NUA has included information sections on how it will support academically low-achieving students, academically high-achieving students, socioeconomically disadvantaged students, English Learners, and students with disabilities. All of the sections, except for supporting socioeconomically disadvantaged students, include detailed supports and interventions the school will provide for the student groups. There are no details provided that show how socioeconomically disadvantaged students will be served. The entire section consists only of the following:

 

“Students who are socioeconomically disadvantaged need opportunities for enrichment. NUA 1001 STEAM provides these opportunities through a rich, well-rounded educational experience. Strategies for NUA 1001 STEAM’s socioeconomically disadvantaged students draw heavily from the core belief that when students are engaged in learning activities that are relevant to the real world, then learning will be more meaningful and comprehension will improve. Every teacher designs lessons that reflect the student’s’ world with an integrated NUA 1001 STEAM focus.”

 

The petition is vague in its description of how it will support socioeconomically disadvantaged students, which make up about 46% of the student population (page 42).

 

4. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on overly optimistic enrollment projections. This is particularly concerning based on NUA’s past history of closing its other charter schools due to low enrollment.

 

Page 38 of the petition has the following projected enrollment table.

5. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on unrealistic Attendance Rate increases. On page 45, NUA has reported a current Attendance Rate of 99.01%. The school’s State Priority Goals for Student Engagement, listed on page 118, indicates that the school will achieve a 3% increase in attendance rates. A 3% increase would put the rate at approximately 101.98%, which is unrealistic.

 

6. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on an inadequate Conflict of Interest Code. On page 146 of the charter petition, NUA has indicated that its board of directors are subject to conflict of interest rules under Sections 1090 and 81000 et seq. of the California Government Code. “In addition, the Board of Directors has adopted a conflict of interest code that complies with the requirements of the Political Reform Act…” NUA included its current Conflict of Interest Policy, which was revised in February 2017, as Appendix I. The policy does not satisfy Government Code Sections 81000 et seq., as stated in the charter, as it lacks required information.

 

District staff has reviewed the attached National University Academy 1001 STEAM charter petition and recommends that the board adopt the above-identified factual findings in support of a denial.

 

Should the board decide to approve the charter petition, in addition to the findings identified above, the following changes to the petition are necessary.

 

  • On page 98 of the petition, it indicates that a “change in LEA status or SELPA membership shall not require a material revision of this charter.” The sentence should be removed as this change would be material revision to the charter.

  • NUA must revise Element Ten (Student Suspension and Expulsion Procedures) to comply with Ed Code section 47605(b)(5)(j).

  • NUA must have its own governing board, separate from the other National University Academy board(s), that will oversee only the NUA Aero Court site. The board should include no more than two current National University Academy board members.

Members of the public who desire to address the board on any topic related to board work, and not on today's regular meeting agenda, are welcome to do so at this time. Speakers are requested to:

  • limit their remarks to not more than 3 minutes;
  • appoint a spokesperson if the concern is a group concern; and,
  • supplement verbal presentation with written reports, if necessary or desired.
